\begin_layout Subsection*
Reference and general idea
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivation of R0 for a SIR type model following description of 'Mathematical
 Tools for Understanding Infectious Disease Dynamics' written by Odo Diekmann,
 Hans Heesterbeek and Tom Britton.
 See chapter 7, section 2 'Next-generation matrix for compartmental systems'.
 We use 4 steps to find the basic reproduction number of a system.
 1) Define the infected subsystem, i.e.
 all equations that include compartments where individuals can get infected.
 2) Linearize the subsystem in the disease free equilibrium.
 3) Find the next generation matrix (NGM) with large domain (
\begin_inset Formula $K_{L}$
\end_inset

) by writing the linear system as: 
\begin_inset Formula $\bs{\dot{x}}=(\bs{T}+\bs{\Sigma})\bs{x}$
\end_inset

, here 
\begin_inset Formula $\bs{x}$
\end_inset

 is a vector containing all states where individuals can get infected, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bs{T}$
\end_inset

 contains all terms corresponding to transmission and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bs{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

 all terms corresponding to transitions between compartments.
 Then: 
\begin_inset Formula $\bs{K}=-\bs{T}\bs{\Sigma}^{-1}.$
\end_inset

 4) The reproduction number is now the dominant eigenvalue of the NGM.
 We also reference the description of R0 in metapopulations in Philipps
 S, Rossi D.
 Mathematical Models of Infectious Diseases: Two-Strain Infections in Metapopula
tions, and the methodology for calculating R0 used by the authors in Gatto
 M, Bertuzzo E, Mari L, Miccoli S, Carraro L, Casagrandi R, et al.
 Spread and dynamics of the COVID-19 epidemic in Italy: Effects of emergency
 containment measures.
 PNAS.
 2020 May 12;117(19):10484â€“91.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Infected subsystem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The infected subsystem is the following: 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\dot{E}_{i}=\lambda_{i}S_{i}-\delta_{E}E_{i}\\
\dot{P}_{i}=\delta_{E}E_{i}-\delta_{p}P_{i}\\
\dot{A}_{i}=(1-f)\delta_{p}P_{i}-\gamma_{A}A_{i}\\
\dot{I}_{i}=f\delta_{p}P_{i}-\kappa_{i}I_{i}\\
\dot{H}_{i}=h_{i}\eta I_{i}-\gamma_{H}H_{i}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where, 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\lambda_{i}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\beta_{ij}\frac{P_{j}+A_{j}+I_{j}+H_{j}}{N_{j}}\label{eq:lambda}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{ij}=\tau C_{ij}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 being the probability of infection for a contact with an infected person,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the average number of contacts of an individual of class 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 with an individual of class 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Parametrization of the contact matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimated the average number of contacts of individuals of class 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in the camps, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}_{i}$
\end_inset

, and we parametrized the contact matrix assuming that, in a well-mixed
 population, these contacts will be distributed among classes relative to
 the fraction of individuals within each class, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C_{ij}=\bar{c}_{i}N_{j}/N,
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 the total population size.
 A well-mixed population will be considered the null model, and parameters
 derived under the null model assumptions are indexed with the superscript
 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, e.g.
 the null contact matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{ij}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The type of interventions that we consider, aim to reduce either the average
 number of contacts a class 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 self-isolation) or the accessibility of class 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to class 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 shielding strategies).
 We model the first type of intervention introducing the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

, representing the fraction of the average number of contacts observed in
 the null model that prevail after the intervention: 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}_{i}=\epsilon_{i}\bar{c}_{i}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, we model the second type of intervention with the management
 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{ij}$
\end_inset

, representing the fraction of population 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 visible to population 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 after the intervention.
 The contact matrix resulting from management strategies can therefore be
 written with respect to the null model as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C_{ij}=\epsilon_{i}m_{ij}\bar{c}_{i}^{0}N_{j}/N=\epsilon m_{ij}C_{ij}^{0}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the parametrization for the null model, we substitute in the expression
 for lambda (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lambda"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) to obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\lambda_{i}=\frac{\tau}{N}\sum_{j=1}^{n}\epsilon_{i}\bar{c}_{i}^{0}m_{ij}\left(P_{j}+A_{j}+I_{j}+H_{j}\right)\label{eq:lambda-1}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Estimation of the Next Generation Matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start considering the subsystem containing the infectious population
 and, to facilitate notation, let us consider the following ordering of
 the variables in the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(E_{1},...,E_{M},P_{1},...,P_{M},A_{1},...,A_{M},I_{1},...,I_{M},H_{1},...,H_{M})$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 the number of population classes.
 Following this notation, the linearized system can be written in the form
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bs{\dot{x}}=(\bs{T}+\bs{\Sigma})\bs{x}$
\end_inset

, where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\bs{T}=\tau\begin{bmatrix}\bs{0} & \bs{\Theta} & \bs{\Theta} & \bs{\Theta} & \bs{\Theta}\\
\bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0}\\
\bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0}\\
\bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0}\\
\bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is the transmission matrix, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bs{\Theta}=\mathrm{diag}(p_{i}\bar{c}_{i})\bs{\bs{U}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=N_{i}/N$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bs{U}$
\end_inset

 being the all-ones matrix of size 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 The transition matrix is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\bs{\Sigma}=\begin{bmatrix}-\delta_{E}\bs{I} & \bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0}\\
\delta_{E}\bs{I} & -\delta_{p}\bs{I} & \bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0}\\
\bs{0} & (1-f)\delta_{p}\bs{I} & -\gamma_{A}\bs{I} & \bs{0} & \bs{0}\\
\bs{0} & f\delta_{p}\bs{I} & \bs{0} & -\mathrm{diag}(\kappa_{i})\bs{I} & \bs{0}\\
\bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0} & \eta\mathrm{diag}(h_{i})\bs{I} & -\gamma_{H}\bs{I}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bs{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bs{0}$
\end_inset

 are the identity and null matrices of size 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{i}=((1-g_{i}-h_{i})\gamma_{I}+h_{i}\eta+g_{i}\alpha)$
\end_inset

.
 We next compute the inverse of the transition matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\bs{\Sigma^{-1}}=\begin{bmatrix}-\frac{1}{\delta_{E}}\bs{I} & \bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0}\\
-\frac{1}{\delta_{p}}\bs{I} & -\frac{1}{\delta_{p}}\bs{I} & \bs{0} & \bs{0} & \bs{0}\\
-\frac{(1-f)}{\gamma_{A}}\bs{I} & -\frac{(1-f)}{\gamma_{A}}\bs{I} & -\frac{1}{\gamma_{A}}\bs{I} & \bs{0} & \bs{0}\\
-f\mathrm{diag}(\frac{1}{\kappa_{i}})\bs{I} & -f\mathrm{diag}(\frac{1}{\kappa_{i}})\bs{I} & \bs{0} & -\mathrm{diag}(\frac{1}{\kappa_{i}})\bs{I} & \bs{0}\\
-\frac{f\eta}{\gamma_{H}}\mathrm{diag}(\frac{h_{i}}{\kappa_{i}})\bs{I} & -\frac{f\eta}{\gamma_{H}}\mathrm{diag}(\frac{h_{i}}{\kappa_{i}})\bs{I} & \bs{0} & -\frac{\eta}{\gamma_{H}}\mathrm{diag}(\frac{h_{i}}{\kappa_{i}})\bs{I} & -\frac{1}{\gamma_{H}}\bs{I}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The NGM with large domain can now be found by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bs{K_{\mathrm{L}}}=-\bs{T}\bs{\Sigma}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, however, as we know that each individual that gets infected first will
 go to the 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 compartment we can instead calculate the NGM with small domain, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf {K_{\mathrm{S}}}}$
\end_inset

 that only consists of the 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 compartment 
